					<div class="inner">
						<p class="article-summary">The girls designed their own mobile applications that addressed a need in their schools or communities. The process included brainstorming, creating an app prototype, “storyboarding” the concept and presenting it.</p>
						
							<p>SMITHFIELD, R.I. — What type of apps do girls want?</p><p>Consider the answers offered by more than two-dozen 9- to 12-year old girls who participated in the App Challenge Saturday at Bryant University.</p><p>The event was the first held by the Fantastic Girltastic Code Company Challenge, a program of the YWCA Rhode Island in partnership with Bryant and Amica Insurance Co. The program aims to “inspire and equip” girls’ to pursue careers in computer sciences by showing them how it’s “relevant, cool, hip and exciting,″ Meghan Grady, chief operating officers of YWCA Rhode Island, said.</p><p>The U.S. is projected to have nearly <a href="http://www.ncwit.org/sites/default/files/resources/btn_02282014web.pdf" target="_blank">1.2 million</a> computing-related jobs by 2020, of which 39 percent — almost 470,000 jobs — which could be filled by undergraduates, according to the National Center for Women &amp; Information Technology.</p><p>On Saturday, the 27 middle-school girls, many of whom attend the Paul Cuffee School, in Providence, a partner in the initiative, designed their own mobile applications that addressed a need in their schools or communities. The process included brainstorming, creating an app prototype, “storyboarding” the concept and presenting it. The were guided by mentors who included women working at Rhode Island companies such as Amica, Mojo Tech and Splatypus Web Design Studio, as well as professors from Bryant and Rhode Island School of Design.</p><p>The girls, who worked in teams, presented their ideas to a panel of judges. The ideas ranged from an app to help you remember to bring your homework home or to school to one designed to challenge gender stereotypes. The winner was a “Superwomen” app which challenges gender stereotypes. The app’s users would be able to create their own superwomen as well as learn about real women who bucked gender stereotypes. The app would be available in the user’s native language and tailored to where they live. </p><div class="adInject" data-gh-lazy-ad-bucket-targeting="{&quot;ad-type&quot;:&quot;Rich Media&quot;,&quot;slot&quot;:&quot;interstitial&quot;,&quot;sov&quot;:&quot;base ROS&quot;,&quot;outofpage&quot;:&quot;interstitial&quot;,&quot;creative-format&quot;:&quot;Interstitial,Outstream Video&quot;,&quot;pageFeature&quot;:&quot;&quot;}" id="interstitial" data-google-query-id="CJ6604ee0OMCFRAdhwoddwUCPQ" style="display: none;"><div id="google_ads_iframe_/11564835/providencejournal.com/news_4__container__" style="border: 0pt none; width: 1px; height: 1px;"></div></div>
<script>
var slotToInject={slotName:"interstitial",ad_type:"Rich Media",sov:"base ROS",outofpage:"interstitial",creative_format:"Interstitial,Outstream Video",slotTrigger:"interstitial",slotTriggerType:"class"};
__gh__webApp.ads.dfp.slot.loadInjected(slotToInject);
</script><div class="adInject" data-gh-lazy-ad-bucket-targeting="{&quot;ad-type&quot;:&quot;Rich Media&quot;,&quot;slot&quot;:&quot;Content Rec 2&quot;,&quot;sov&quot;:&quot;base ROS&quot;,&quot;outofpage&quot;:&quot;Content Rec 2&quot;,&quot;creative-format&quot;:&quot;Content Rec&quot;,&quot;pageFeature&quot;:&quot;&quot;}" id="contentRec2" data-google-query-id="CJuquIee0OMCFU4Whwod4Z8N3A"><div id="google_ads_iframe_/11564835/providencejournal.com/news_3__container__" style="border: 0pt none;"><iframe id="google_ads_iframe_/11564835/providencejournal.com/news_3" title="3rd party ad content" name="google_ads_iframe_/11564835/providencejournal.com/news_3" width="1" height="1" scrolling="no" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" frameborder="0" style="border: 0px; vertical-align: bottom;" data-google-container-id="7" src="./CodingMarlainaMe_files/saved_resource(4).html"></iframe></div></div>
